Scanning and enumeration are two common techniques for gathering information about hosts and services on a network. Scanning refers to the use of various tools and techniques to survey a network for active hosts, open ports, and the types of services running on those ports. Enumeration refers to gathering detailed information about the discoveries made using scanning techniques, such as the operating system running on those hosts, the version of software running on its open ports, and even vulnerabilities associated with those versions.

One of the oldest and most popular tools in the space is Nmap (“Network Mapper”), a network exploration and security auditing tool. Originally conceived for quickly mapping hosts in large networks, it has since developed additional functionality well beyond its humble origins.

In this lab, you will learn about four of the phases in an Nmap scan ( there are eleven in total). The first two are focused on initial scanning, and the latter two are focused on enumerating details about the discovered hosts and services. They are:

  • Host Discovery (also called Ping scanning)
  • Port Scanning
  • Operating System Detection
  • Service/Service Version Detection

Also - if the term “port” is unfamiliar for you, let’s catch you up with a quick primer, as this concept will be foundational to understanding much of this lab. Otherwise, you can skip the indented section ahead.

A Quick Note on Ports - Ports are how network applications are identified on a host. A host can be identified by its IP address—this is like the street address for an apartment complex. To send mail to a specific person in that complex, you would need to put a unit number. That’s a port. 

Furthermore, you’ll be hunting for services running on TCP ports, the most common type of ports found on the Internet. TCP is a network protocol, which is just a set of rules and specifications that specifies how systems should communicate – in other words, a language. Computers are literal, they need rules to follow. TCP has one particularly important rule – connections must begin with a 3-way handshake. It goes:

1. Client: SYN (synchronize)

2. Server: SYN/ACK (synchronize/acknowledge)

3. Client: ACK (acknowledge)

Boom – you’ve established a TCP connection. And now you can speak TCP. Say it fast, it’s fun: SYN, SYNACK, ACK. Again. SYNSYNACKACK (Mars Attacks, anyone?)

That handshake rule makes scanning for TCP ports easy – a service on that port is always going to respond to a connection request (SYN or synchronize) if the port is open. 

Okay, you’re all caught up – now, back to Nmap.

Whether scanning for open ports or enumerating services and versions on a host, Nmap takes the same approach: send data, analyze the response. As part of its analysis, Nmap maintains a database of “fingerprints” - composite profiles that it compares responses against. If it can get a host to talk enough, it can sufficiently disambiguate from the alternatives. Consider the following example, in which you are trying to distinguish two people from one another, Mary and Molly. 

You say “Hello”, and both Mary and Molly respond with “Hello.” Then you say “Hello, how are you,” and Mary responds, “I am well, how are you” while Molly responds, “Good and you?”.

Now, pretend that’s the way they will almost always respond. At this point, you know sending a “Hello” does not provide you enough information to infer details about who it is. But sending a “hello, how are you” does provide enough detail to differentiate them.

Great, now you’ve found a strategy for differentiating the two from one another - congratulations, you’ve become a fleshy Nmap.

Nmap is a powerful utility used by network administrators to inventory hosts on a network, defensive security experts to map their attack surface area, and offensive security experts to detect firewalls and find vulnerable hosts and services they may leverage to demonstrate impact as part of a security audit. In this lab, you will use Nmap to ask questions, obtain answers, and learn a little about how to interpret those answers.

In the next steps, you will:

  • Fire off two scans on your in-lab workstation to get comfortable.
  • Review several of the options available for augmenting your scans.
  • Review the output.

This will prepare you for the next lesson, where you will scan and enumerate the rest of the target network.

  1. On the dock at the bottom of the screen, click the Terminal Emulator icon to open a Terminal window.
  2. At the cybrary@clabnet prompt, type clabnet and press Enter to start the network emulator.

    You will receive a new terminal window once the network initializes.
    This Node (h1) terminal is your rental for this lab - your workstation within clabnet.
  3. In the Node (h1) window, type nmap 192.168.0.1 and press Enter to run your first Nmap scan on the h1 machine.
    This is your first TCP connect scan – congratulations! You can specify this type of scan using the option -sT, but it is also the default when running without root privileges. This type of scan, also known as full-open, performs a full 3-way handshake to complete a connection to the service running on a port. Here you can see an open port (22) on your machine.

    If run as root, Nmap will default to a SYN stealth scan, which you can specify using -sS.
  4. In the Node (h1) window, type sudo nmap 192.168.0.1 and press Enter to run a default Nmap scan with root privileges.
    This type of scan, also known as half-open, does not complete the TCP handshake – it initiates the connection, and once it gets a response, it immediately terminates it.

    As you can see, it also identified one additional port. Typically, both TCP scan types will reveal the same ports, but it is not uncommon to see variations in results between the various scanning techniques.

    You should see one open port, one filtered port, and the remaining 998 ports as closed (Not shown: 998 closed ports. Nmap scans the top 1000 most common ports by default). These are the three primary port states that Nmap will report, and they are defined as follows.

         Open – the port is reachable and a service is listening on it.

         Closed – the port is reachable and no service is listening on it.

         Filtered – the port is not reachable so I cannot tell (usually indicates a firewall).

    There are other states which can be viewed at https://nmap.org/book/man-port-scanning-basics.html, but are not often encountered until you engage in more advanced scanning techniques.

Now that you are familiar with the basic functionality of Nmap, let's briefly review a common subset of the options you will be exploring in this lab. You can obtain a complete list of Nmap options at nmap.org or by executing nmap -h in your terminal. 

Nmap syntax is flexible, so options may be placed in any order after the command. For example, the following commands are both valid and will produce the same results:

  • nmap -Pn -sS -F -T4 127.0.0.1 
  • nmap -F -T4 127.0.0.1 -sS -Pn

Port Specification

  • -p <port num> - Specifies port(s) to scan. Can be a single port, a range, a comma-separated list, or any combination of those. 

    By default, Nmap scans the top 1000 ports (not 1-1000, but the 1000 most frequently used ports – think 80 for HTTP, 443 for HTTPS, etc).
  • -F - Fast (shorthand for “top 100 ports”). Equivalent to –top-ports 100.

Ping Types

  • -Pn - Disables host discovery (treats all hosts as online). This is the only one you will use in this lab.

​​Scan Types

  • -sT - TCP connect scan, also called a “full-open” scan. Completes the TCP handshake, then terminates the connection (SYN, SYN/ACK, ACK, ACK, RST).

    This is the default scan if running Nmap without root privileges. 
  • -sS - SYN stealth scan, also called a “half-open” scan, because it begins and then abruptly ends the 3-way handshake with a reset packet (SYN, SYN/ACK, RST). “Stealth” here refers to application logging (if connection doesn’t complete, probably won’t be logged), although modern firewall and IDS/IPS solutions are likely to detect such unusual traffic. It is not necessarily stealthier than full-open scans, which are likely to detect such unusual traffic. But it is faster and lower bandwidth!

    This is the default scan if running Nmap with root privileges.
  • -sn - Ping scan (disables scanning, so only host discovery is performed).

Fingerprint Operating Systems & Versions

  • -O - ​​Detect the operating system running on the host. If the target system is a close enough match to an OS fingerprint in Nmap’s database, it will report the OS. Otherwise, you can force it to guess more aggressively by adding –osscan-guess.
  • -sV - Detect the network service and version running on a host’s open network ports. This provides some additional information about the host operating system, though the primary aim is to identify vulnerable services (for patching or exploiting, depending on your role).

Timing

  • -T1-5 - Timing templates for adjusting your scan speed. These templates are categorized as Paranoid (0) | Sneaky (1) | Polite (2) | Normal (3) | Aggressive (4) | Insane (5). 

    The default is Normal (3).

Alright, brain and fingers are warmed up? Answer the questions in the Tasks tab, then it's time to get to work on the rest of the network.
